## Slide 3 — Problem Statement & Motivation

**What's on it:** Left — bullet points about skin cancer stats. Right — ISIC 2024 challenge block.

**What to say (30 sec):**
> "Skin cancer is the most common cancer globally — one-third of all diagnosed cancers. Melanoma specifically causes the majority of skin cancer deaths. The key issue is early detection: at Stage I survival is above 99%, but at Stage IV it drops below 30%. There's also limited access to dermatologists, especially in rural areas. 
>
> The ISIC 2024 Challenge on Kaggle provides 401,000 lesion records with both 3D Total Body Photography metadata and dermoscopic images. The primary metric is partial AUC above 88% TPR — meaning the model must maintain high sensitivity to catch cancers."

---

## Slide 4 — Dataset Overview

**What's on it:** Left — dataset stats table + alert block on imbalance. Right — feature categories.

**What to say (30 sec):**
> "The dataset has 401,059 samples from 1,942 patients. The critical challenge is extreme class imbalance — only 393 samples are malignant, that's 0.098%. The ratio is approximately 1:1,020 benign to malignant. A naïve classifier predicting all benign would get 99.9% accuracy but would be clinically useless.
>
> Features include patient demographics, anatomical site, and 3D Total Body Photography measurements — colour statistics in RGB, HSV, and L*a*b* colour spaces, spatial ratios, and border complexity. Plus dermoscopic images in HDF5 format."

**If professor asks "Why is accuracy a bad metric?":**
> "Because with 99.9% benign, you get 99.9% accuracy by predicting all benign. pAUC above 88% TPR forces the model to maintain high recall for the malignant class."

---

