## Slide 7 — Feature Engineering (55 → 98)

**What's on it:** Four categories of engineered features with formulas.

**What to say (40 sec):**
> "In Phase 1, we engineered 43 new features from the 55 raw columns, giving us 98 total features in four categories:
>
> **First, ratio features** — we compute lesion-to-skin colour ratios like x_i divided by x_j. These relative contrasts are robust across different skin types.
>
> **Second, polynomial interaction features** — products of pairs of features to model non-linear relationships, for example border complexity times colour variation.
>
> **Third, per-patient statistical aggregations** — this is the most impactful category. We compute how each lesion deviates from that patient's personal baseline. A 'dark' lesion on a fair-skinned patient has different meaning than on a dark-skinned patient. We calculate z-scores using patient-specific mean and standard deviation.
>
> **Fourth, target-encoded categorical features** — anatomical site values encoded using fold-safe target encoding."

**If professor asks "Why fold-safe?":**
> "If we compute target encoding on the full dataset, the validation set's labels leak into the training features. We compute statistics only on each fold's training set."

---

## Slide 8 — Phase 1 Models & Results

**What's on it:** Left — models description + ensemble formula. Right — results table + ROC curves.

**What to say (40 sec):**
> "We trained two gradient-boosted tree models. **LightGBM** uses histogram-based leaf-wise tree growth — fast on large datasets. **XGBoost** uses L1+L2 regularised objectives. Both use StratifiedGroupKFold with K=5 by patient ID, and scale_pos_weight of approximately 1020 to handle class imbalance.
>
> The ensemble combines both models using pAUC-weighted averaging — the model with higher pAUC gets higher weight.
>
> Results: LightGBM achieved AUC 0.821 and pAUC 0.030. XGBoost significantly outperformed at AUC 0.915 and pAUC 0.066. The ensemble gives a slight further improvement to AUC 0.917 and pAUC 0.068. XGBoost's explicit regularisation proved more effective for this extreme imbalance."

---

## Slide 9 — CNN Architecture: EfficientNet-B4-NS

**What's on it:** Left — why B4-NS, head architecture. Right — configuration table.

**What to say (40 sec):**
> "For Phase 2, we use EfficientNet-B4 with NoisyStudent pretraining. **Why B4?** B0 has only 5.3M parameters — it underfits lesion details at 256×256. B7 has 66M parameters — far too many for only 393 positives, it would just memorise them. B4 at 19.3M is the sweet spot.
>
> **Why NoisyStudent?** It's a semi-supervised pretraining approach where a student model is trained on pseudo-labelled data with added noise. This produces more robust, generalisable features that transfer better from ImageNet to the medical domain.
>
> The classification head is simple: Global Average Pooling, then Dropout at 0.4, then a single Linear layer outputting a raw logit — no sigmoid — for compatibility with Focal Loss."

**If professor asks "Why no sigmoid?":**
> "Focal Loss internally computes sigmoid. Using BCEWithLogitsLoss is more numerically stable than applying sigmoid + BCELoss separately."

---

## Slide 10 — Focal Loss

**What's on it:** Left — formula + why not BCE. Right — focal loss curves plot.

**What to say (40 sec):**
> "Standard Binary Cross-Entropy is dominated by the 400,000 easy benign samples. Focal Loss from Lin et al.'s 2017 RetinaNet paper solves this.
>
> The formula is: FL(p_t) = minus alpha_t times (1 - p_t) to the power gamma times log(p_t).
>
> The key is the modulating factor **(1 - p_t)^γ** with gamma = 2. When the model is correct on a benign sample with confidence 0.95, p_t = 0.95, and (1-0.95)² = 0.0025 — the loss is reduced by **400 times**. But when the model misclassifies a malignant sample with p_t = 0.1, (1-0.1)² = 0.81 — the full gradient signal is preserved.
>
> In the plot on the right, you can see: gamma=0 is standard BCE; as gamma increases, the loss for well-classified examples drops dramatically. We use gamma=2 as recommended by Lin et al."

---

## Slide 11 — Data Augmentation Pipeline

**What's on it:** Left — 9 transforms + MixUp formula. Right — augmentation grid image.

**What to say (30 sec):**
> "We built a 9-transform pipeline using Albumentations, each justified for dermoscopy. Flips — because lesions have no orientation. ShiftScaleRotate — simulating camera positioning. BrightnessContrast and HueSaturation — for scanner variation. CoarseDropout — forces the model to spread attention rather than fixating on one small region. GaussianBlur and GridDistortion for optical artefacts.
>
> Additionally, MixUp blends pairs of images with lambda drawn from Beta(0.4, 0.4), acting as a label-space regulariser critical when training on only 393 positives."

---

## Slide 12 — Learning Rate Schedule

**What's on it:** Left — warmup + cosine annealing explanation. Right — LR schedule plot.

**What to say (25 sec):**
> "The learning rate follows two phases. **Linear warmup** for the first epoch — LR ramps from zero to 2×10⁻⁴. This prevents the randomly initialised classification head from corrupting the pretrained backbone with large initial gradients.
>
> Then **cosine annealing** from epoch 2 to 12 — LR smoothly decays to 2×10⁻⁶, which is 1% of the base. The cosine curve avoids abrupt drops and gives better convergence than step decay."

---

## Slide 13 — Negative Subsampling & CV Alignment

**What's on it:** Left — subsampling strategy. Right — CV alignment + data format.

**What to say (25 sec):**
> "Training on all 400k images is computationally prohibitive. So we keep only **12% of benign samples** per fold — about 48,000 — while keeping all 393 positives. This is combined with pos_weight in Focal Loss. Importantly, subsampling applies **only to the training set** — the full validation set is always used.
>
> Crucially, we use the **same GroupKFold splits as Phase 1**. This ensures fair OOF comparison and enables proper late fusion without information leakage."

---

## Slide 14 — MixUp in Practice

**What's on it:** Left — MixUp visualisation image. Right — formula and details.

**What to say (20 sec):**
> "Here you can see MixUp in practice — pairs of training images are blended with coefficient lambda. The loss is also blended: lambda times loss on label A plus (1-lambda) times loss on label B. This smooths the decision boundary and acts as an implicit data augmentation, creating virtual training examples in the convex hull of the data distribution."

---

## Slide 15 — Grad-CAM Theory

**What's on it:** Left — algorithm steps. Right — clinical value.

**What to say (30 sec):**
> "Grad-CAM from Selvaraju et al. produces saliency maps showing which image regions drove the prediction. The algorithm: we do a forward pass to get feature map activations A^k, then backward pass to get gradients. We global-average-pool the gradients to get importance weights alpha_k, then compute a weighted sum of feature maps passed through ReLU.
>
> The clinical value is threefold: verifying the model looks at lesion regions not artefacts, identifying failure modes, and building clinician trust."

---

## Slide 16 — Grad-CAM Visualisations (NEW)

**What's on it:** Actual Grad-CAM images from trained model — true predictions and failure cases.

**What to say (25 sec):**
> "Here are the actual Grad-CAM outputs from our trained CNN. On the left, true predictions with overlaid saliency. On the right, failure cases. The observation is that the CNN produces diffuse, ring-shaped attention rather than focused lesion-specific saliency. This indicates the model did not learn fine-grained discriminative features for distinguishing malignant from benign."

---

## Slide 17 — Late Fusion

**What's on it:** Fusion formula, grid search strategy, why late fusion.

**What to say (25 sec):**
> "Late fusion combines the two modalities: y_final = alpha times tabular OOF plus (1-alpha) times CNN OOF. Alpha is optimised via grid search over 101 steps, maximising pAUC on the out-of-fold predictions. Because both modalities use the same CV folds, this introduces no information leakage.
>
> We chose late fusion because the two modalities have complementary signals — tabular captures patient risk factors and colour statistics, while CNN captures spatial texture patterns — and each can use its own optimal architecture."

---

## Slide 18 — Results Table (KEY SLIDE)

**What's on it:** Results table with all models + ROC comparison plot.

**What to say (30 sec):**
> "Here are the combined results. Phase 1: LightGBM at AUC 0.821, XGBoost at 0.915, tabular ensemble at **0.917 AUC and 0.068 pAUC**. Phase 2: CNN alone at **0.78 AUC and 0.02 pAUC**.
>
> The CNN is significantly weaker than the tabular ensemble. With only 393 positive images among 401,000 total and extreme 1:1,020 imbalance, the CNN struggled to learn discriminative visual features. The tabular ensemble remains the dominant modality — the rich 3D-TBP metadata already encodes colour and border statistics that gradient boosted trees exploit very effectively."

