## Common Professor Questions & Answers

### Q: "Why not use SMOTE or other oversampling for the tabular models?"
> "We experimented with majority subsampling via `majority_subsample_fraction` in our config, but found that using all training rows with `scale_pos_weight=1020` worked better. SMOTE creates synthetic samples in feature space which can introduce noise with high-dimensional features. The gradient-boosted trees handle imbalance natively through the class weighting."

### Q: "Why GroupKFold instead of regular StratifiedKFold?"
> "Patients have multiple lesions — up to hundreds. If patient A's lesions appear in both train and validation, the model memorises patient-specific characteristics rather than learning general lesion features. GroupKFold ensures all of one patient's lesions stay in the same fold, preventing this data leakage."

### Q: "Why did you choose pAUC as the metric?"
> "It's the official ISIC 2024 competition metric. Clinically, missing a melanoma — a false negative — is far more dangerous than a false positive. pAUC above 88% TPR focuses evaluation on the high-sensitivity zone where the model must catch at least 88% of cancers."

### Q: "Could you use a Vision Transformer instead of EfficientNet?"
> "Yes, ViTs like DeiT or Swin Transformer could be used. However, ViTs typically need more training data to outperform CNNs. With only 393 positives, an inductive-bias-rich architecture like EfficientNet (with its convolutional priors) is a safer choice. ViTs would be more promising with external pre-training on larger dermatology corpora."

### Q: "What is the difference between AUC and pAUC?"
> "AUC is the area under the full ROC curve — it measures discrimination across all thresholds. pAUC restricts this to only the region where TPR ≥ 88%. In clinical settings, we only care about the high-sensitivity operating region, so pAUC is more relevant."

### Q: "Why is the CNN weaker than the tabular model?"
> "Three reasons: (1) the tabular features already encode the discriminative colour and border statistics in numerical form — trees exploit this directly. (2) 393 positive images are genuinely too few for a CNN to learn subtle dermoscopic patterns. (3) The domain gap from ImageNet to medical imaging reduces the value of transfer learning."
